      },
      "lineNbr": 29,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000000
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-21T16:20:41Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "💯 .  \n\nI\u0027ll elaborate why in another comment but I would not be in favor of any AI attribution, but I would be strongly opposed to \"must\" or \"should\" language.  There are multiple cases in my own flow at the top of mind where I could not specify this properly.\n\n1. I usually use opencode as my \"AI agent\".  While I have a few models that I typically default to, I don\u0027t really want to keep track of which model I used for a particular commit.  I may switch between models in the course of creating a commit (or commit series).  Also, opencode will sometimes \"fall back\" to different models when it gets an error from the API endpoints.\n\n2. Meta, having their own foundational LLM model development, has internal models that I can use for OpenBMC development which may be unreleased and/or unannounced.  I would not be able to reference the model being used and even if I were able to it would have to be an internal codename which is probably not useful.\n\nBeyond that, how are we going to know if someone doesn\u0027t specify?  Are we going to start using an LLM-grader like colleges have to _detect_ [potentially] generated code?",
      "parentUuid": "48796a4b_a0f02c9a",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 29,
        "startChar": 66,
        "endLine": 29,
        "endChar": 73
      },
      "revId": "96e8aa85d7872b993a2ac5871b7a77f2e4855a08",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "138f7a35_65e4c43c",
        "filename": "coding-assistants.md",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 29,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000153
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-21T16:53:17Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Andrew, ack on \"can\".\n\nPatrick, how are you handling that for kernel contributions then if your AI models are private?  I care a lot less about the specific model used.  In the above case, I\u0027d assume \"opencode\" would just be your agent name?\n\nWhy does \"knowing\" matter in the context of this?  We can assume good intent from people submitting.  This isn\u0027t meant to be a police action, it\u0027s intended to know that when we see a hallucination, or something that doesn\u0027t make sense, we can add the appropriate pointers so that those AIs can generate the correct code the first time.",
      "parentUuid": "56f0ea86_2d10918d",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 29,
        "startChar": 66,
        "endLine": 29,
        "endChar": 73
      },
      "revId": "96e8aa85d7872b993a2ac5871b7a77f2e4855a08",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "cbd8babd_2d61c6e0",
        "filename": "coding-assistants.md",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 29,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000000
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-21T17:20:44Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e how are you handling that for kernel contributions then if your AI models are private? \n\nI don\u0027t do much kernel development and I haven\u0027t seen any internal discussion on this.  I can start it.\n\n\u003e I\u0027d assume \"opencode\" would just be your agent name?\n\nThe kernel seems all over the place.  Most show \"Claude:claude-...\".  I don\u0027t even know what \"Claude\" refers to in this case because I image most kernel developers are using `claude-cli` if they referenced `Claude` here.\n\nhttps://gist.github.com/williamspatrick/597965579f12eb7695a923407d41e1d2",
      "parentUuid": "138f7a35_65e4c43c",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 29,
        "startChar": 66,
        "endLine": 29,
        "endChar": 73
      },
      "revId": "96e8aa85d7872b993a2ac5871b7a77f2e4855a08",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "c2b3ccb8_ff863cc4",
        "filename": "coding-assistants.md",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 45,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000000
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-21T16:20:41Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I don\u0027t think that knowing the AI model is beneficial to us other than \"what are people using that they\u0027ve found success with\".  I do think that it adds risk to the project.  For that reason I would not be in favor of anything strong than \"can\" and I would rather it is not encouraged.\n\nWhile we have said on line 22 that the human submitter is \"responsible for ensuring compliance with licensing requirements\" and \"taking full responsibility for the contribution\" practically speaking nobody (even the best copyright lawyers) cannot say what the final copyright implications are of LLM generated code yet because it really hasn\u0027t gone through any court cases.  Every contributor is just going to say \"yeah, yeah, whatever ... this works and I\u0027m going to submit it\".\n\nLF makes this statement in their [LLM policy]:\n\n\u003e Some tools provide features that can assist contributors. For example, some tools provide a feature that suppresses responses that are similar  to third party materials in the AI tool’s output, or a feature that flags similarity between copyrighted training data or other materials owned by third parties and the AI tool’s output and provides information about the licensing terms that apply to such third party materials. \n\nThe implication of that is effectively: \"some tools and/or models might be generating code that is too similar to training data and might be ruled as a copyright violation in the future\".  If a few years from now there are court cases around this, we may find that company X or tool A did it \"right\" while company Y or tool B did it \"wrong\" in terms of how the training and/or generation lines up with legal precedent.\n\nBy putting the Assisted-by tag in here we make it far easier for someone to say \"you were using a \u0027bad\u0027 tool and I\u0027m going to assert copyright violations\" or for some of the participants of the project here to deem there is too much legal risk because too many of our commits used a \"bad bad\" (unless we go through a huge effort to rewrite all code that we generated by _Bad Model_.  If we leave this out we put the onus on the IP owners to find and assert so-called violations (and we make it harder on them to find and filter).\n\n[LLM policy]: https://www.linuxfoundation.org/legal/generative-ai",
      "revId": "96e8aa85d7872b993a2ac5871b7a77f2e4855a08",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
